Focussing on AI through services route; intends to remain asset light
CITI On HCL Tech
Neutral, TP Rs 1600
Reported a good 2Q – revenues ahead & raised lower end of services revenue guidance
Fwd. looking indicators
(a) Overall revenue guidance unchanged at 3-5% yoy cc; services now at 4-5% (earlier 3-5%);
(b) Headcount +3.7% yoy
(c) LTM TCV +13% yoy;
(d) Mgmt. commentary – external environment unpredictable; business indicators promising
Raise FY27E-FY28E EPS est. by 0-1%
CLSA on HCL Tech
O-P, TP Rs 1660
Strong 2Q beat across revenue growth, Ebit margin and order booking.
It revised upwards its services business revenue growth guidance to 4-5% (from 3-5%) on back of 2Q beat and good visibility for 2H on back of strong deal wins.
For overall revenue growth though, it kept the 3-5% FY26 guidance band intact due to weakness in the software business
Believe key to HCL’s re-rating from current levels depends on Ebit margin recovering back to 18-19% in FY27
GS on HCL Tech
Maintains Neutral with a target price of ₹1,620 (vs 1,530 earlier)
Q2FY26 growth outpaced peers, with 2.4% QoQ CC revenue rise and headcount addition showing improving demand
Share gains in key renewals suggest company-specific strength rather than broad industry momentum
Some deal declines tied to Al productivity gains setu may weigh on sector valuations
FY26 services growth guidance raised to 4-5%, with expectations near ~5.1%
Nuvama on HCL Tech
Recommendation Hold; Target Price ₹1,650, Earlier Target ₹1,630
Valuations are on a par with TCS and Infosys, we see limited upside potential
Sequential broad-based growth with improved margins
Strong client interest with Al force now deployed in 47 accounts (versus 35 QoQ)
USB on Autos
While street thinks that GST cuts will lead to a medium-term entry-level and 2W demand revival, our analysis, past precedent & channel checks show consumers want to trade up to premium.
Meanwhile, upcoming regulatory changes (CAFE, 2W ABS) & state government tax hikes may erode the GST cut benefits
Prefer premiumization plays M&M, TVS & Hyundai (all Buy), while see downside risk for Hero, Bajaj (both Sell) & Maruti (Neutral)
CLSA on Autos
GST boost well-timed amid weak Q1 demand.
Consumers shifting to premium models per channel checks.
CAFE norms & ABS may dilute GST benefit.
CLSA prefers M&M, TVS, Hyundai as premiumisation plays.
Ambit on LG Electronics
